AB  - With the rapid development of wireless communications and multimedia technologies, humans are increasingly seeking more immersive and multidimensional sensory experiences beyond traditional audio-visual demands. This has led to the emergence of multi-modal services, which further integrate haptic modality signals and are poised to become the next generation of multimedia services in the 6th-generation (6G) era. Examples of multi-modal services include industrial manipulation, e-health care, remote education, and more. To adequately facilitate these multi-modal services, this work pioneers a new approach: cross-modal collaborative communications, an emerging paradigm with significant potential. The fundamental goal of cross-modal collaborative communications is to overcome barriers and fully leverage the potential correlations among audio, visual, and haptic modality signals within multi-modal services. By doing so, cross-modal collaborative communications can effectively meet the requirements of low latency, high reliability, and high throughput. Specifically, on one hand, a content-driven scheduling scheme has been designed by leveraging the spatio-temporal transmission characteristics among audio, visual, and haptic modalities. On the other hand, a complete cross-modal signal restoration, reconstruction, and rendering architecture has been developed through semantic-based signal fusion and sharing among different modalities. Evaluation results demonstrated that the cross-modal collaborative communications can improve the immersive experience of the user substantially and considerably.
ER  - 

