AB  - Human-Computer Interaction (HCI) continues to evolve, bridging the gap between humans and technology by creating intuitive, engaging, and efficient interactive systems. Among these innovations, smart table systems have emerged as a promising solution for environments like restaurants and collaborative workspaces. However, these systems often face challenges in understanding user preferences, fostering engagement, and delivering seamless interaction. Traditional input methods, such as touch-based controls, fall short of providing the natural, immersive experiences that users now expect from interactive systems. Therefore, this study investigates alternative interaction techniques to traditional HCI methods, focusing on hand gestures, Tangible User Interfaces (TUI), and Augmented Reality (AR) to evaluate their usability and effectiveness in smart table interactions. Hand gestures enable a contactless and intuitive interface, allowing users to interact naturally. Tangible User Interfaces (TUIs) provide a tactile dimension by enabling interaction with physical objects, enhancing engagement, while Augmented Reality (AR) integrates virtual and physical elements to create immersive experiences. A user study evaluated these methods, focusing on task completion times, learning curves, and overall usability. The results highlight that while hand gestures proved the most efficient and intuitive, Tangible User Interfaces (TUIs) and Augmented Reality (AR) provided distinct advantages in engagement and immersion. This analysis highlights the strengths and weaknesses of each technique, providing insights into their effectiveness for smart table interactions.
ER  - 

